England":"Nedging, Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Munning","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: relationship name from the Middle English personal name  <i>Munding</i> (Old English * <i>Munding</i>, a derivative of names in  <i>Mund-</i> or  <i>-mund</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Munnings","meanings":["English (Suffolk): variant of <b>Munning</b>, with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. <b>Munning</b> is from the Middle English personal name <i>Munding</i> (Old English <i>Munding</i>, a derivative of names in <i>Mund-</i> or <i>-mund</i>). This form of the surname is the more common one in Britain."]}]},{"name":"Gilbert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. This was the name of the founder of the only native British religious order (abolished at the Dissolution of the Monasteries),  St Gilbert  of Sempringham (  ?1083–1189 ), in whose honour it is still sometimes bestowed, especially among Roman Catholics. It gained a wider currency in the 19th century."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":22,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705197,"age":95,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Gilbert Munning was born about 1360, in Poitiers, Vienne, Poitou-Charentes, France. He married Charlotte of Poitiers in 1385, in Poitiers, Vienne, Poitou-Charentes, France. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1459, in Nedging, Suffolk, England, at the age of 100, and was buried in Poitiers, Vienne, Poitou-Charentes, France."},"et":{"about 1360–1459":"umbes 1360–1459","1364–1463":"1364–1463","1386–1443":"1386–1443","1390–1424":"1390–1424","1360–1459":"1360–1459","about 1360":"umbes 1360","1385":"1385","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1390":"1390","1459":"1459","Abt 1361":"umbes 1361","1424":"1424","1455":"1455","1443":"1443","1386":"1386","1463":"1463","1364":"1364","about 1400":"umbes 1400","about 1361":"umbes 1361","Poitou, France":"Poitou, Prantsusmaa","Poitiers, Vienne, Poitou-Charentes, France":"Poitiers, Vienne, Poitou-Charentes, Prantsusmaa","of Poitou, France":"Poitou, Prantsusmaa","Poitiers, Departement de la Vienne, Poitou-Charentes, France":"Poitiers, Vienne, Poitou-Charentes, Prantsusmaa","Nedging, Suffolk, England":"Nedging, Suffolk, England"},"fi":{"about 1360–1459":"noin 1360–1459","1364–1463":"1364–1463","1386–1443":"1386–1443","1390–1424":"1390–1424","1360–1459":"1360–1459","about 1360":"noin 1360","1385":"1385","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1390":"1390","1459":"1459","Abt 1361":"noin 1361","1424":"1424","1455":"1455","1443":"1443","1386":"1386","1463":"1463","1364":"1364","about 1400":"noin 1400","about 1361":"noin 1361","Poitou, France":"Poitou, Ranska","Poitiers, Vienne, Poitou-Charentes, France":"Poitiers, Vienne, Poitou-Charentes, Ranska","of Poitou, Fr